ps offered alternative accounts of this narrative in order to legitimise contemporary political programmes based on different versions of national identity. It then looks at how these debates were manifested in social activities as diverse as football, religion, economics and language. This book attempts to make an important contribution to both the way we study nationalism and national identity, and our understanding of post-Yugoslav politics and society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNational characteristics, Croatian. 0aNationalismzCroatia. 0aNationalism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Nationalism & Patriotism.2bisacsh  aCroatia.  adiaspora groups.  adissident intellectuals.  agovernment.  anational identity.  anational state.  anationalism.  aopposition parties.  apolitics.  asociety.1 aBellamy, Alex J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526137739zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526137739zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526137739/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA